,Not Recommended,402130,31203467,Posted: 17 April,all,Willie989,"Its leaps and bounds better than 3. It really is. It's still very rough though.Positives:Decent amount of carsCars can be upgradednew stuntsunlockable rocket trails and hornsIt actually feels like FlatOut.Negatives:If you slam into an NPC, they take very little damage (even if you hit them at 200+), yet if they hit you, it takes BIG chunks out. Yes, there's a stat that effects damage dealt, but this was truck V car, and the car won.If you try to push an NPC, well... You're better off trying to push a steam roller with a tricycle. They're massively heavier in their punch buggy than you are in your pickup truck.The flipping is real. hit any item heavier than a fence, and you'll roll. Get hit by a car, and you roll. Hit a small bump in the terrain, and you'll roll. I'm resetting my car almost as much as I'm driving.There aren't enough courses for the number of career races. You'll do the same track across all 3 series many times over. It becomes a grindfest.The cash gain feels low. Unless you're spending the entire race mashing the crap out of the NPCs, you won't get much money at all.The reward screens are punishing. you have to stare at your reward for a good 3-4 seconds each before you can move on, and you tend to get 2-6 rewards per cup. That's up to 1/2 a minute of just staring at text mashing enter just waiting for a chance to play again per cup. Worst part about it: you're mashing enter. as soon as you collect the last reward, you suddenly get back to menus with zero delay. What that means for you: you launch yourself into another race before you even realize you collected the final reward. Now you have to sit through TWO loading screens just to get back to the garage, like you haven't been waiting long enough in the first place. Almost as aggrevating as the AI.Overall a good game, brought down by artificial difficulty due to the AIs' weight/durability advantages and odd physics. Still a great game to play with friends though; the online portion isn't nearly as painful as single player. It's deffinately a leap in the right direction for the FlatOut series."
